summary:
The Security Council,
 Reiterating its primary responsibility for international peace and security, and promoting respect for international humanitarian law,
 Reaffirming resolutions 1296 (2000), 1265 (1999), and 1460 (2003) on protection of civilians, children, and humanitarian personnel,
 Welcoming General Assembly resolutions on the safety of humanitarian personnel and UN personnel,
 Reaffirming humanitarian personnel's obligation to respect host country laws and uphold neutrality, impartiality, and humanity,
 Emphasizing existing prohibitions under international law against attacks on humanitarian personnel,
 Gravely concerned at violence against humanitarian personnel, including the August 19, 2003, attack on UNAMI in Baghdad,

1. Condemns all forms of violence against humanitarian personnel, including murder, rape, and harassment;
2. Urges States to ensure punishment for crimes against humanitarian personnel;
3. Reaffirms parties' obligation to comply with international law protecting humanitarian personnel;
4. Urges allowing unimpeded access and necessary facilities for humanitarian operations;
5. Determines to ensure safety and security of humanitarian personnel through:
(a) Inclusion of Convention provisions on prevention of attacks and prosecution of offenders in agreements;
(b) Secretary-General to bring to Council's attention situations where humanitarian assistance is denied due to violence;
(c) Declaration of exceptional risk under the Convention, where circumstances support it.
The Security Council 
Requests the Secretary-General to address in all his country-specific situation reports, the issue of the safety and security of humanitarian personnel and United Nations and its associated personnel, including specific acts of violence against such personnel, remedial actions taken to prevent similar incidents and actions taken to identify and hold accountable those who commit such acts, and to explore and propose additional ways and means to enhance the safety and security of such personnel.
